---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="System Prompt">
  <main class="main-content" style="width:100%">
    <div class="apa-paper">
      <div class="running-head">
        <span>SYSTEM PROMPT DOCUMENTATION</span>
        <span class="page-num">1</span>
      </div>
      <div class="apa-content">
        <h1>AI System Prompt: Constructing an Astro Textbook Website</h1>
        <p class="no-indent" style="text-align:center; font-style:italic">OpenTextbook Project Documentation</p>

        <div class="abstract">
          <h2>Abstract</h2>
          <p>
            This document presents the cleaned-up system prompt used to instruct an AI coding
            assistant to build a complete academic textbook website using Astro, Tailwind CSS, and
            TypeScript. The prompt specifies the navigation architecture, content hierarchy, visual
            design conventions, sample content requirements, and technical implementation details
            necessary to produce a functional, production-ready static site.
          </p>
        </div>

        <h2>Introduction</h2>
        <p>
          The following prompt was provided to an AI assistant (GitHub Copilot) to scaffold and
          implement a full-featured open textbook website. The site is styled after APA-7 journal
          articles and organizes academic content across a five-level hierarchy: Topics, Books,
          Units, Chapters, and Sections. The prompt is reproduced below in full, lightly edited for
          clarity and readability.
        </p>

        <h2>The Prompt</h2>

        <h3>Overview and Goal</h3>
        <p>
          Build a complete <strong>Astro.build</strong> textbook website. The repository currently
          contains only a <code>README.md</code>. Create a fully functional Astro application with
          rich academic content, APA-7 visual styling, and a navigable content hierarchy.
        </p>

        <h3>Navigation Structure</h3>
        <p>
          Implement a top navbar with dropdown menus that organize content as:
          <strong>Topic → Book → Unit → Chapter</strong>. From the Chapter view, users navigate
          between Sections using forward/back pagination. The navbar dropdowns should function
          with vanilla JavaScript—no front-end framework is required.
        </p>

        <h3>Content Hierarchy</h3>
        <p>
          The content is organized across six levels: Topics &gt; Books &gt; Units &gt; Chapters
          &gt; Sections &gt; Subsections &gt; Sub-subsections. Each level has its own index page
          that lists child items with links. The deepest navigable level (Section) displays the
          full academic content.
        </p>

        <h3>Section View Layout</h3>
        <p>
          The section view includes three parts: (1) a left sidebar with nested subsection
          navigation that highlights the active subsection on scroll; (2) a main content area
          rendering the section text in APA-7 format; and (3) forward/back pagination between
          sections. A breadcrumb at the top shows the full path: Topic &gt; Book &gt; Unit &gt;
          Chapter &gt; Section.
        </p>

        <h3>Visual Design: APA-7 Journal Article Format</h3>
        <p>
          All section content pages should visually resemble a LaTeX-generated APA-7 journal
          article. Design specifications include:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Font: Times New Roman or equivalent serif font at 12pt equivalent</li>
          <li>Line spacing: double-spaced</li>
          <li>Margins: 1-inch equivalent on all sides</li>
          <li>Running head in the header with the article title in uppercase</li>
          <li>Page number in the upper right corner</li>
          <li>APA heading levels: H1 centered bold, H2 flush-left bold, H3 flush-left bold italic</li>
          <li>Paragraphs indented 0.5 inches (except first paragraph after a heading)</li>
          <li>The "paper" rendered as a white card with a shadow on a gray background</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Sample Content Requirements</h3>
        <p>
          Populate the site with real academic content organized as follows:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Topic 1: Mathematics</strong> — Book: <em>Calculus: A Complete Course</em>
            with units on Limits &amp; Continuity and Differentiation. Each unit contains 2–3
            chapters; each chapter contains 3–4 sections with 2–3 subsections and 1–2
            sub-subsections each.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Topic 2: Psychology</strong> — Book: <em>Introduction to Psychology</em>
            with units on Foundations of Psychology and Cognition &amp; Perception. Same
            structural depth as the Mathematics content.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          All section content should consist of genuine academic prose (multiple paragraphs)
          appropriate to the subject matter, not placeholder text.
        </p>

        <h3>Technical Stack and Architecture</h3>
        <p>
          The technical requirements are as follows:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Framework:</strong> Astro (latest version, static output mode)</li>
          <li><strong>Styling:</strong> Tailwind CSS via <code>@astrojs/tailwind</code></li>
          <li><strong>Language:</strong> TypeScript (strict mode)</li>
          <li><strong>Routing:</strong> File-based with <code>getStaticPaths()</code> for all dynamic segments</li>
          <li><strong>Data:</strong> All content defined in <code>src/data/content.ts</code> with typed interfaces</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>File Structure</h3>
        <p>
          The required file structure includes: <code>src/components/</code> (Navbar, Breadcrumb,
          Sidebar, Pagination); <code>src/layouts/</code> (BaseLayout, SectionLayout);
          <code>src/pages/</code> with nested dynamic routes following the content hierarchy;
          <code>src/data/content.ts</code>; and <code>src/styles/global.css</code>.
        </p>

        <h3>Data Structure</h3>
        <p>
          Define TypeScript interfaces for SubSubsection, Subsection, Section, Chapter, Unit,
          Book, and Topic. Export a <code>topics</code> array as the root data source. Provide
          helper functions <code>getAllSections()</code> (returning a flat list with full
          navigation context) and <code>getSectionNav()</code> (returning prev/next section
          objects for pagination).
        </p>

        <h3>Implementation Requirements</h3>
        <p>
          All files must be created. TypeScript and build errors must be resolved before
          submission. The build command <code>npm run build</code> must succeed with zero errors.
          After creating all files, commit everything with the message:
          <em>"feat: build complete Astro textbook website"</em>.
        </p>

        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
        <p>
          The prompt described above was executed by GitHub Copilot to produce this website.
          The resulting application demonstrates the feasibility of using AI-assisted development
          to scaffold complex, content-rich static sites from a single, well-structured prompt.
          The site achieves all specified requirements: dual-topic academic content, APA-7 visual
          design, nested navigation, and a fully functional static build.
        </p>

        <h2>References</h2>
        <p class="no-indent" style="padding-left:0.5in;text-indent:-0.5in">
          American Psychological Association. (2020). <em>Publication manual of the American
          Psychological Association</em> (7th ed.). https://doi.org/10.1037/0000165-000
        </p>
        <p class="no-indent" style="padding-left:0.5in;text-indent:-0.5in">
          Astro contributors. (2024). <em>Astro documentation</em>. https://docs.astro.build/
        </p>
        <p class="no-indent" style="padding-left:0.5in;text-indent:-0.5in">
          GitHub. (2024). <em>GitHub Copilot documentation</em>. https://docs.github.com/copilot
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
